Comment: Dear Governor Perdue: As you have recently demonstrated your concern in the area of health care with the ban on smoking, I wanted to remind you of the recent changes proposoed by the DMA and the devestating consequences for all North Carolinians (not just Medicaid clients) if these changes become policy. What follows is a copy of my letter to the DMA. I trust that as a governor of the people, you will give it your full attention. Thank you. ï»¿ To the DMA: I am gravely concerned about the proposed changes in Medicaid PDN. I believe these changes devalue the lives of Medicaid clients. Not only are the proposals medically dangerous, they will ultimately prove to be more costly than the funding dollars they purport to save. In the area of Congregate Nursing, if both clients experience medical emergencies at the same time, the nurse will be forced to choose which client to place into a life-threatening situation. Medical complications, such as transmission of diseases, multiply if clients are sharing a nurse as proven by studies of nosocomial infections. With the 16 hours-a-day cap, not all adult clients reside with family members capable of providing skilled care or receiving medical training. The additional requirement of Back-Up Care would seem to place the burden of acquiring personnel on the client, increasing stress both emotionally and financially. The Overnight Travel/Vacation Care provision creates a potentially dangerous situation if travel is required for out-of-own medical treatment. The client would either have to travel without a nurse or by the expense of ambulance. The provision potentially creates a civil rights issue as travel to Raleigh to meet with representatives and present arguments to the House and Senate could be impeded. Also, the lack of respite for caregivers will increase risk of mental health crises, further endangering the client. The Technological Point Assessment Ranking System disallows the medical needs of individual clients. Ultimately this ranking would lead to the reduction of skilled monitoring by nurses. For Ventilator Dependent Trach Patients, the inability to provide additional care due to lack of financial or caregiver resources will lead to these clients either trying to find a nursing home that can accommodate them or an ICU. Most nursing homes in North Carolina do not accept ventilator clients due to the level of care needed. The expense of ICU hospitalization versus home care for this population can hardly justify the adoption of these proposals. The possibility of blatant violation of the Olmstead ruling is also evident here. In addition to the arguments against the proposed PDN changes presented above, I would like to remind the DMA of its commitment to quality medical services for low income individuals. To shift the burden of financial responsibility to those clients least able to bear it is inefficient at best and immoral at worst. Thank you for your time in consideration of these statements. Sincerely, Teresa Staley (336) 299-1247

