As a concerned citizen, as well as an employee of a Local Management Enity, I feel that I must speak out in regard to the proposed House budget cuts to mental health, developmental disability and substance abuse (mh/dd/sa) programs in North Carolina.
I have worked in the mh/dd/sa service field for eight years now, as a paraprofessional, case manger, advocate and service analyst. I have witnessed first hand the upheaval caused to individuals receiving services, by state mental health reform. Now, just as we were finding some stability, the proposed budget cuts will eliminate or drastically reduce services to individuals in our community and across North Carolina.
My objections to the proposed cuts are as follows:
* Individuals who are receiving mh/dd/sa services need stability to maintain their progress and remain in their community.
* The proposed cuts will reduce or eliminate the services these individuals need to remain in their communities and have productive lives.
* Reduction in jobs in health and human services and education will result in less services and increasing demands.
* Individuals and families will lose crucial services and local governments are not in the position to fill the void
* The proposed cuts will lead to an increase in jail populations and hospital emergency departments will be overwhelmed because individuals are coming in who need mh/dd/sa services and have no where else to go.
* The proposed cuts will lead to more hospitalizations due to lack of services in the individuals community.
* Due to the proposed cut of 465 undefined positions, which will impact the state run hospitals that most of the individuals in my community utilize, state hospitals will not have the staff to meet the increase in individuals needing hospitalization.
* Last year Crossroads was able to respond to more that 9,000 citizens in Iredell, Surry and Yadkin counties, almost 2,000 needing and receiving services with in two hours. If funding is cut there will be an increase in suicides because there wont be help available within two hours.
* Crossroads used the LME Fund Balance this current fiscal year to mitigate the state budget cuts and continue providing services to our citizens. If this funding is reduced we will not be able ensure that services will be there for our citizens. We have already been asked by our contract providers for more funds so they can expand their programs to meet the demand but we have not been able to do this. If funding is reduced we may not be able to fund the programs we already have let alone have funds to expand services.
* There has been much in the news in the last year about the misuse of community support services. Yes, there were some community support providers that misused the service but on the whole there are hundreds of providers who use the service appropriately and help individuals get back on their feet and become productive citizens in their community. If funding is cut for these services what will happen to these individuals? I fear they will be in jail, in an institution or dead.
* When I was still on the service delivery side of mh/dd/sa services I worked with an individual who had been diagnosed with Bipolar Disorder and Alcohol Abuse. This individual was an alcoholic for 20 years, could not maintain a job and was arrested multiple times. With the support of mental health and substance abuse services this individual has been sober for 9 years, completed his GED and is taking college courses. He has also discovered his artistic talents, creating designs for flowerpots and woodwork that he can sell through local business. Without support I fear this individual will decompensate and either end up in jail or institution.
In conclusion I would like to ask that you consider the upheaval already caused by mental health reform to individuals in services, their families and communities and vote against these proposed cuts. In these tough economic times we all must make sacrifices, but to sacrifice our most vulnerable citizens is morally wrong and irresponsible. It will cost more in the end (human lives) than it will save
